    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-02-01T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-02-01T04:00:00-05:00" n="325"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/502: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-02-01T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 1, 1939—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Reference my January 31, 6 p.m. to Hankow<note n="78" xml:id="d325fn78">Not
                        printed.</note> and Tokyo’s No. 52, January 31, noon, concerning return of
                    Americans to Hankow.</p>
                <p>In a conversation this morning the local Japanese Consul General confirmed that
                    the transport was the <hi rend="italic">Shinyo Maru</hi> and that it carried to
                    Hankow a party of foreigners. He stated that any information to the contrary
                    obtained in Tokyo must have been due to a misunderstanding.</p>
                <p>The essentials are that American business interests are unable to send their
                    representatives to Hankow (and other Yangtze ports) because of Japanese
                    restriction and that American interests are suffering therefrom.</p>
                <p>Sent to Tokyo. Repeated Department, Peiping, and Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
